WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.910 --> 00:00:04.000
MALE SPEAKER: Hello,
and welcome everyone

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:07.824
to another episode of our
Value investing Series.

00:00:07.824 --> 00:00:10.620
We have a very special
guest with us today.

00:00:10.620 --> 00:00:14.090
So in thinking about
introducing him,

00:00:14.090 --> 00:00:18.270
I have to start off with
a series of experiments,

00:00:18.270 --> 00:00:20.000
a series of studies
that were done

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:22.820
at Stanford by the
professor Walter

00:00:22.820 --> 00:00:26.130
Mischel in 1960s and '70s.

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:29.980
These are also most widely known
as the Stanford Marshmallow

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:32.830
Experiment that you
might have heard of.

00:00:32.830 --> 00:00:36.310
Essentially, it
was an experiment.

00:00:36.310 --> 00:00:38.810
It was basically a bunch of
studies in which children were

00:00:38.810 --> 00:00:43.350
offered a choice between
one small reward provided

00:00:43.350 --> 00:00:47.480
immediately, or two small
rewards if they waited

00:00:47.480 --> 00:00:52.150
for a short period, which was
about 15 minutes, during which

00:00:52.150 --> 00:00:56.870
the tester would leave
the room and then return.

00:00:56.870 --> 00:01:00.160
The reward was sometimes
a marshmallow, but often

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:02.310
a cookie or a pretzel.

00:01:02.310 --> 00:01:05.710
In followup studies, what
these researchers found

00:01:05.710 --> 00:01:07.930
was very surprising.

00:01:07.930 --> 00:01:11.430
These children who were able to
wait longer for the preferred

00:01:11.430 --> 00:01:15.670
rewards tended to have
better life outcomes

00:01:15.670 --> 00:01:20.170
as measured by SAT scores,
educational attainment, body

00:01:20.170 --> 00:01:25.040
mass index, and
other life measures.

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:27.470
Now why am I mentioning this?

00:01:27.470 --> 00:01:30.780
Our guest today is no
psychology professor.

00:01:30.780 --> 00:01:34.190
But he happens to
be a Stanford alum.

00:01:34.190 --> 00:01:38.490
And he happens to be a
world famous value investor.

00:01:38.490 --> 00:01:42.810
In speaking about his investing
process and philosophy,

00:01:42.810 --> 00:01:46.440
you will see parallels
between delayed gratification.

00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:48.810
Let me share a quote
from his recent interview

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:50.320
with all of you.

00:01:50.320 --> 00:01:52.860
He describes his
process saying, "We

00:01:52.860 --> 00:01:56.840
tend to benefit in life when
we sacrifice something today

00:01:56.840 --> 00:01:59.070
to gain something tomorrow.

00:01:59.070 --> 00:02:00.540
That is true for companies.

00:02:00.540 --> 00:02:02.790
That is true for individuals."

00:02:02.790 --> 00:02:05.440
His focus, he says,
is on businesses

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:09.449
that have the capacity to
suffer, that is, they can

00:02:09.449 --> 00:02:13.590
reinvest their capital
at high rates of return

00:02:13.590 --> 00:02:17.120
so that the wealth will
continue to compound

00:02:17.120 --> 00:02:20.150
into years into the future.

00:02:20.150 --> 00:02:24.190
Thomas Russo, our guest,
is a preeminent investor

00:02:24.190 --> 00:02:28.800
of our times who began his
investing journey in 1982

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:32.390
after an encounter
that changed his life.

00:02:32.390 --> 00:02:36.380
He was studying law and
business as a graduate student

00:02:36.380 --> 00:02:40.350
at Stanford when Warren Buffett
came to address his investment

00:02:40.350 --> 00:02:42.060
class.

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:45.560
As Mr. Russo explained
in a recent interview,

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:48.350
he was dazzled by the
speed of Buffett's mind,

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:51.980
his quirky delivery,
and his beguiling

00:02:51.980 --> 00:02:57.050
habit of courting everyone from
Bertrand Russell to Yogi Berra

00:02:57.050 --> 00:03:01.020
and the wisdom of his
deeply thought ideas.

00:03:01.020 --> 00:03:05.460
This inspired him to finding
his own investment vehicle

00:03:05.460 --> 00:03:09.730
and starting his value
investing journey.

00:03:09.730 --> 00:03:12.630
We are so glad that
he's here in person

00:03:12.630 --> 00:03:14.910
to share his experience
and his journey

00:03:14.910 --> 00:03:18.090
and his insights
with all of us here.

00:03:18.090 --> 00:03:19.410
Thank you for coming.

00:03:19.410 --> 00:03:21.720
So without any further
ado, ladies and gentlemen,

00:03:21.720 --> 00:03:25.494
please join me in welcoming
the one and only Thomas Russo.

00:03:25.494 --> 00:03:30.124
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:30.124 --> 00:03:31.790
THOMAS RUSSO: I'm so
pleased to be here.

00:03:31.790 --> 00:03:34.154
I actually thought
the setting would

00:03:34.154 --> 00:03:35.320
be a much different setting.

00:03:35.320 --> 00:03:41.050
I thought we'd be underground
in some catacombs with a group

00:03:41.050 --> 00:03:43.430
of people worshipping
an outlawed

00:03:43.430 --> 00:03:46.770
faith in Silicon Valley, the
faith of value investing.

00:03:46.770 --> 00:03:49.280
But here we are, next
to the free food,

00:03:49.280 --> 00:03:51.520
the wonderfully lit
room, great chairs.

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:55.870
So being a zealot in the
investment business today

00:03:55.870 --> 00:03:58.170
doesn't bear the marks
that it did 2000 years ago

00:03:58.170 --> 00:04:00.460
for religious zealots, I guess.

00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:04.910
It's a great honor to be
here, especially at this time.

00:04:04.910 --> 00:04:08.810
It's a really good excuse to
get away from the markets, which

00:04:08.810 --> 00:04:11.210
is something that's welcome.

00:04:11.210 --> 00:04:14.560
Even though I say that, we've
had an unusual period of time

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:17.940
which reaffirms what
[? Surapa ?] described

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:22.720
as this value investing
preference for businesses that

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:26.360
have the capacity to
suffer, because you think

00:04:26.360 --> 00:04:31.060
about my last three years,
we've certainly suffered when

00:04:31.060 --> 00:04:35.560
compared to the S&amp;P 500, which
has been elevated by sort

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:36.917
of global capital flows.

00:04:36.917 --> 00:04:39.000
And we've had businesses
that, right through this,

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.730
have been investing in
their strong global brands,

00:04:41.730 --> 00:04:45.760
but showing a modest growth
at the reporting level

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:51.450
because they often invest a
portion of their net profits

00:04:51.450 --> 00:04:53.880
against future
business prospects.

00:04:53.880 --> 00:05:00.330
Now recently, almost a third of
our portfolios in beverages--

00:05:00.330 --> 00:05:03.820
and the world is now quite
reaffirmed about the value

00:05:03.820 --> 00:05:08.080
of beverage brands through
the noise about the AB InBev

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:10.590
acquisition of SABMiller--
we own both those shares,

00:05:10.590 --> 00:05:14.260
and it's helped generate
performance recently

00:05:14.260 --> 00:05:16.810
in the face of a
plunging market.

00:05:16.810 --> 00:05:19.520
And then I was reminded
of this again today, which

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:23.770
was the results of an
announcement by JT Tobacco

00:05:23.770 --> 00:05:29.590
to acquire American Spirit
from Reynolds American Tobacco.

00:05:29.590 --> 00:05:31.970
Well, quite
extraordinarily, the price

00:05:31.970 --> 00:05:33.890
was almost Silicon Valley-like.

00:05:33.890 --> 00:05:37.160
It was 300 times
operating income

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:40.265
for a business-- they paid
$5 billion for a business

00:05:40.265 --> 00:05:43.850
that I think had around
$500 million in revenue,

00:05:43.850 --> 00:05:46.780
much smaller base of
profits because it's still

00:05:46.780 --> 00:05:48.790
investing in its own growth.

00:05:48.790 --> 00:05:51.750
But they saw something that they
could take around the world.

00:05:51.750 --> 00:05:57.660
And it reaffirms-- within
a business like RJR,

00:05:57.660 --> 00:06:02.340
where people often
overlook the investment

00:06:02.340 --> 00:06:04.739
because it lacks sizzle-- that
the strength of the brand,

00:06:04.739 --> 00:06:06.780
the predictability of cash
flow, and the ability,

00:06:06.780 --> 00:06:09.570
most importantly, to reinvest
that cash flow going forward--

00:06:09.570 --> 00:06:11.080
leaves it quite valuable.

00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:15.060
I'm going to come over here so
I can move some of these around.

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:18.170
I did, in fact, also
welcome the chance

00:06:18.170 --> 00:06:19.990
to come up because
I'll talk tomorrow

00:06:19.990 --> 00:06:22.390
to the students in Professor
Jack McDonald's class, which

00:06:22.390 --> 00:06:24.310
I've done for the
past 25 years, having

00:06:24.310 --> 00:06:25.590
graduated from his class.

00:06:25.590 --> 00:06:28.220
And it was there that
Buffettt came to our class

00:06:28.220 --> 00:06:33.160
and provided some
early insights.

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:35.640
I'll go through a
couple of quick slides.

00:06:35.640 --> 00:06:39.160
As an investor, you're always,
at least in the value investing

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:42.040
world, encouraged to
invest for the long term

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:45.220
and let market disruptions
pass you by, hold on.

00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:48.090
And I was reminded of
this in June of 2008,

00:06:48.090 --> 00:06:51.610
when I was in Africa with
my family on a safari.

00:06:51.610 --> 00:06:53.970
And every day we'd go
out to visit the range

00:06:53.970 --> 00:06:55.610
and look for animals.

00:06:55.610 --> 00:06:58.080
Each one looks more
ferocious than the next.

00:06:58.080 --> 00:07:01.150
And every single time,
the guide would say, look,

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:04.110
if you're ever separated from
the group, and you're alone,

00:07:04.110 --> 00:07:06.280
and you're being charged
by a lion or anything

00:07:06.280 --> 00:07:09.080
else-- a chameleon,
anything that

00:07:09.080 --> 00:07:11.719
might come at you-- freeze,
and it'll ignore you,

00:07:11.719 --> 00:07:12.510
run right past you.

00:07:12.510 --> 00:07:14.380
But if you run,
they'll chase you down.

00:07:14.380 --> 00:07:16.370
That was the rule again
and again and again.

00:07:16.370 --> 00:07:18.300
Finally we came upon this guy.

00:07:18.300 --> 00:07:20.650
And he said that,
that's a Cape Buffalo.

00:07:20.650 --> 00:07:23.620
If ever you're alone and
you're separated from the group

00:07:23.620 --> 00:07:27.860
and you see one coming
charging at you, run like hell.

00:07:27.860 --> 00:07:31.020
And so that happened
in June of 2008,

00:07:31.020 --> 00:07:32.950
when the market was
just in free fall.

00:07:32.950 --> 00:07:35.180
And at the time, I sort
of felt like maybe we

00:07:35.180 --> 00:07:36.280
should run like hell.

00:07:36.280 --> 00:07:38.880
We didn't, and we haven't.

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:40.380
It's my belief,
it's been my belief,

00:07:40.380 --> 00:07:42.770
that equities are
the preferred form

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:48.100
of investing for one capable
of enduring short-term pain

00:07:48.100 --> 00:07:49.110
for long-term gain.

00:07:49.110 --> 00:07:51.120
Equities will be the
best way to do that.

00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:53.110
And along that
line, I would just

00:07:53.110 --> 00:07:55.526
want to make a point about
this other Stanford experiment

00:07:55.526 --> 00:07:56.400
that you referred to.

00:07:56.400 --> 00:08:00.310
I do believe definitely in
deferral in the investment

00:08:00.310 --> 00:08:02.640
world-- as you can see,
a little less as it

00:08:02.640 --> 00:08:03.730
comes to marshmallows.

00:08:03.730 --> 00:08:07.150
I tend to grab the big
ones and eat them quickly.

00:08:07.150 --> 00:08:09.490
But the principle's the same.

00:08:09.490 --> 00:08:12.130
In fact, I incorporate
the principle in one

00:08:12.130 --> 00:08:14.250
of the early
lessons that Buffett

00:08:14.250 --> 00:08:16.890
gave at an annual meeting
of Berkshire, where he said,

00:08:16.890 --> 00:08:20.710
you know, really, investing is
as simple as "Aesop's Fable."

00:08:20.710 --> 00:08:25.370
It's about the bird in hand
versus the bird in the bush.

00:08:25.370 --> 00:08:28.590
The only thing you need to
know-- because you know what

00:08:28.590 --> 00:08:31.290
you have-- what you need to
know, which is uncertain,

00:08:31.290 --> 00:08:33.490
is what you'll end up with when.

00:08:33.490 --> 00:08:36.730
And he says, it's
as easy is that,

00:08:36.730 --> 00:08:39.380
and then he says,
it's as hard as that.

00:08:39.380 --> 00:08:41.720
I'm in an audience at Google.

00:08:41.720 --> 00:08:44.850
And I think I read
that the minutes spent

00:08:44.850 --> 00:08:48.850
on YouTube in the last second
quarter versus the prior year

00:08:48.850 --> 00:08:52.170
was up 60%, and that's
on a million users.

00:08:52.170 --> 00:08:55.730
And I can tell you that if you
keep up that type of growth

00:08:55.730 --> 00:08:56.980
rate, it won't take that long.

00:08:56.980 --> 00:08:59.229
You'll know what you're going
to have, which is a lot,

00:08:59.229 --> 00:09:01.050
and it's going to happen soon.

00:09:01.050 --> 00:09:02.670
But in most
businesses you're not

00:09:02.670 --> 00:09:04.410
blessed with 60% growth rates.

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:07.830
There's something
much less commanding.

00:09:07.830 --> 00:09:11.930
But it is about what
you'll end up with.

00:09:11.930 --> 00:09:14.740
And so I think
that's a good emblem.

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:17.720
This I take from one of
our largest holdings,

00:09:17.720 --> 00:09:18.870
which is Nestle.

00:09:18.870 --> 00:09:23.490
They, like Google,
talk extensively

00:09:23.490 --> 00:09:26.550
about corporate
culture, because that

00:09:26.550 --> 00:09:29.855
is what you can bank on
when you make an investment.

00:09:32.980 --> 00:09:34.880
We own businesses
that are supposed

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:36.540
to reproduce
themselves over time,

00:09:36.540 --> 00:09:38.020
and you need a strong culture.

00:09:38.020 --> 00:09:42.270
And the head of Nestle's Japan
business once showed this slide

00:09:42.270 --> 00:09:44.660
and remarked about
how lovely he thought

00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:47.340
that 700-year-old temple was.

00:09:47.340 --> 00:09:50.320
And then he said, now, none
of the wood's 700 years old,

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:52.080
but the temple is.

00:09:52.080 --> 00:09:54.490
And I thought of that as
sort of an apt metaphor

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:55.874
for what businesses are like.

00:09:55.874 --> 00:09:58.040
I mean, none of you will
be at Google at some point,

00:09:58.040 --> 00:10:00.599
but Google will hopefully
still be Google.

00:10:00.599 --> 00:10:02.140
The timbers are all
changed out here,

00:10:02.140 --> 00:10:03.765
but it still stands
for the same thing.

00:10:03.765 --> 00:10:07.600
And you'll be a very different
company when you're all gone.

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:09.510
But Google should
still stand, in light

00:10:09.510 --> 00:10:12.450
of its context at that
time, as a business

00:10:12.450 --> 00:10:14.680
with the same virtues and
values as it is today.

00:10:14.680 --> 00:10:17.230
And that corporate
culture is extraordinarily

00:10:17.230 --> 00:10:21.970
important to myself because
most of the money that I oversee

00:10:21.970 --> 00:10:25.430
is invested through me by
wealthy families, family

00:10:25.430 --> 00:10:26.360
offices.

00:10:26.360 --> 00:10:29.580
And for them, it helps
a lot to hold a business

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:30.480
for a very long time.

00:10:30.480 --> 00:10:32.470
And the only way
you can invest based

00:10:32.470 --> 00:10:36.520
on that belief is if you get
the corporate culture right

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:42.160
I came out of Warren Buffett's
visit to my class in 1982

00:10:42.160 --> 00:10:44.580
at Stanford Business School
with a couple of sets

00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:46.750
of information captured here.

00:10:46.750 --> 00:10:48.670
First, the $0.50 dollar bill.

00:10:48.670 --> 00:10:50.830
That used to be the
old-fashioned way of thinking

00:10:50.830 --> 00:10:51.850
about value investing.

00:10:51.850 --> 00:10:55.280
If you buy $0.50 dollar bill,
your margin of safety was quite

00:10:55.280 --> 00:10:57.640
great because of the discount.

00:10:57.640 --> 00:11:01.970
Your internal rate of return,
however, depended exactly

00:11:01.970 --> 00:11:04.554
on when that discount closed.

00:11:04.554 --> 00:11:06.970
And if it closed in a year,
you'd make 100% on your money.

00:11:06.970 --> 00:11:10.960
If it took 10 years, you'd
make 7% on your money,

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:14.020
and so on through
the Rule of 72.

00:11:14.020 --> 00:11:18.320
It's also problematic
because it's taxable.

00:11:18.320 --> 00:11:22.050
So in that old model, if
you took that $0.50 dollar

00:11:22.050 --> 00:11:25.450
and realized the dollar,
you'd pay 40% tax on that now

00:11:25.450 --> 00:11:28.814
because long term gains
have been less favored.

00:11:28.814 --> 00:11:30.230
And you have to
redeploy the money

00:11:30.230 --> 00:11:31.700
into finding something else.

00:11:31.700 --> 00:11:33.920
That didn't seem like
much of a thoughtful way

00:11:33.920 --> 00:11:36.150
to conduct affairs
from my perspective,

00:11:36.150 --> 00:11:38.180
especially since,
at business school,

00:11:38.180 --> 00:11:43.230
Warren gave the class
the primary benefit.

00:11:43.230 --> 00:11:44.940
He talked about
the only one thing

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:47.510
that the government gives
you as an investor, which

00:11:47.510 --> 00:11:50.493
is the non-taxation
of unrealized gains.

00:11:50.493 --> 00:11:51.993
They give you one
other thing, which

00:11:51.993 --> 00:11:55.022
is that you can deduct
losses for tax purposes.

00:11:55.022 --> 00:11:56.480
But you don't you
want to go there.

00:11:56.480 --> 00:11:58.650
You're much better
off finding something

00:11:58.650 --> 00:12:02.040
that you could hold so that the
gains that you get over time

00:12:02.040 --> 00:12:03.500
are unrealized.

00:12:03.500 --> 00:12:06.080
So when he spoke at
our class, Berkshire

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:08.370
traded at $900 a share.

00:12:08.370 --> 00:12:11.020
Today it's at $200,000 a share.

00:12:11.020 --> 00:12:12.145
It's never paid a dividend.

00:12:12.145 --> 00:12:14.570
It's never done anything
except compound.

00:12:14.570 --> 00:12:18.020
And it's only because
he's been able to reinvest

00:12:18.020 --> 00:12:20.660
at such a high rate internally.

00:12:20.660 --> 00:12:24.680
And rather than try to close the
discount, the discount that we

00:12:24.680 --> 00:12:27.430
started with, he just
let the intrinsic value

00:12:27.430 --> 00:12:31.530
compound and the market price
will track it over time.

00:12:31.530 --> 00:12:32.570
It

00:12:32.570 --> 00:12:34.760
Warren also said
that there aren't

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:36.990
that many good
businesses in the world.

00:12:36.990 --> 00:12:39.060
As an investor you
should select a business

00:12:39.060 --> 00:12:41.330
that you find interesting
so you would follow it

00:12:41.330 --> 00:12:43.310
and you spend more time with it.

00:12:43.310 --> 00:12:47.480
For me, that was
consumer brands.

00:12:47.480 --> 00:12:52.680
Early Buffett
investing was sort of

00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:56.810
transformed once Berkshire
bought See's Chocolate

00:12:56.810 --> 00:12:57.830
in the early '70s.

00:12:57.830 --> 00:13:01.280
And I heard from him
early into that exercise,

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:04.700
but he already had realized
that See's gave him the ability

00:13:04.700 --> 00:13:08.050
to raise prices regularly,
because the consumer doesn't

00:13:08.050 --> 00:13:12.760
believe that there's an adequate
substitute for the brands

00:13:12.760 --> 00:13:15.420
that they embrace.

00:13:15.420 --> 00:13:18.010
I recognized that once
flying on an airplane,

00:13:18.010 --> 00:13:21.050
and the person next to me
ordered a Jack Daniels.

00:13:21.050 --> 00:13:23.680
The steward said, sorry, we
just have Jim Beam, and he said,

00:13:23.680 --> 00:13:24.869
I'll have water.

00:13:24.869 --> 00:13:26.285
I'd rather have
water than the one

00:13:26.285 --> 00:13:28.910
that I don't really
identify with.

00:13:28.910 --> 00:13:31.210
And that brand
loyalty, by the way,

00:13:31.210 --> 00:13:34.060
is what we look for at the
heart of our businesses.

00:13:34.060 --> 00:13:38.230
That gives pricing power, that
gives predictability of demand.

00:13:38.230 --> 00:13:41.960
In fact, it's that brand
loyalty that, at some point,

00:13:41.960 --> 00:13:44.820
you guys are involved with
creating and sustaining

00:13:44.820 --> 00:13:48.960
through all of the work
that happens at Google.

00:13:48.960 --> 00:13:51.412
But that's the sort
of uber brand value

00:13:51.412 --> 00:13:52.870
rather than the
search brand value.

00:13:52.870 --> 00:13:54.328
So we can talk
about that later on,

00:13:54.328 --> 00:13:57.130
because I'm intrigued by Google.

00:13:57.130 --> 00:13:58.130
So what did Warren say?

00:13:58.130 --> 00:14:01.800
He said margin of
safety's required.

00:14:01.800 --> 00:14:06.410
The $0.50 dollar bill, however,
changed by the time I met him,

00:14:06.410 --> 00:14:08.924
because he realized that a
business that can price has

00:14:08.924 --> 00:14:11.340
the ability to grow, and that
growth is more powerful than

00:14:11.340 --> 00:14:14.990
discounts of inert value.

00:14:14.990 --> 00:14:18.900
He said, observe the tax
efficiency of holding.

00:14:18.900 --> 00:14:20.850
And then he said,
you're probably

00:14:20.850 --> 00:14:24.757
going to have to find managers
who are owner-minded if you're

00:14:24.757 --> 00:14:27.090
going to hold for a long time,
because otherwise they'll

00:14:27.090 --> 00:14:28.270
steal from you.

00:14:28.270 --> 00:14:30.610
So the question is agency
costs, and that's actually

00:14:30.610 --> 00:14:33.870
at the heart of the
investment contract

00:14:33.870 --> 00:14:36.460
that you have with your
public company managers.

00:14:36.460 --> 00:14:38.620
There is a contract that
says, you'll have the use

00:14:38.620 --> 00:14:41.015
of my money, my
investors' money,

00:14:41.015 --> 00:14:42.890
but you have to treat
it as if it's your own.

00:14:42.890 --> 00:14:45.760
You can't prefer your
returns to their returns.

00:14:45.760 --> 00:14:47.420
That's very hard to find.

00:14:47.420 --> 00:14:52.210
And so in my world, where
I found it to be available

00:14:52.210 --> 00:14:55.690
is through
family-controlled companies

00:14:55.690 --> 00:15:00.000
where the family exercise
dominion on their own rights

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.330
over the management to do
what's right for the next 10

00:15:04.330 --> 00:15:06.040
generations of the family.

00:15:06.040 --> 00:15:08.010
That's starts to feel
comfortable to me because

00:15:08.010 --> 00:15:09.320
of my long-term mindedness.

00:15:09.320 --> 00:15:12.710
I like businesses that invest
for the very longest term,

00:15:12.710 --> 00:15:16.810
and do so with the owner in
mind rather than management.

00:15:16.810 --> 00:15:22.840
The average US public
company, by contrast,

00:15:22.840 --> 00:15:25.450
has no family entanglements.

00:15:25.450 --> 00:15:26.430
It's purely public.

00:15:26.430 --> 00:15:30.050
There's absolutely no
image of a shareholder

00:15:30.050 --> 00:15:34.340
when people think
about the contract.

00:15:34.340 --> 00:15:38.120
I actually met the CFO
of Coca Cola recently,

00:15:38.120 --> 00:15:41.020
and she referred to shareholders
as stakeholders, and I said,

00:15:41.020 --> 00:15:42.977
don't you really mean owners?

00:15:42.977 --> 00:15:44.560
Because the word
stakeholder-- I mean,

00:15:44.560 --> 00:15:46.810
you could be a stakeholder
if you're the community,

00:15:46.810 --> 00:15:48.060
if you're this or you're that.

00:15:48.060 --> 00:15:49.960
There are all these concepts.

00:15:49.960 --> 00:15:54.460
But in business, what you really
want your agents to think about

00:15:54.460 --> 00:15:56.890
is the owner at some level.

00:15:56.890 --> 00:15:58.641
Public companies
are so far removed

00:15:58.641 --> 00:15:59.890
from that it's not even funny.

00:15:59.890 --> 00:16:03.500
Really, it's the idea of how do
you make the public company's

00:16:03.500 --> 00:16:05.310
money manage its money?

00:16:05.310 --> 00:16:09.860
The most efficient way designed
to do that are stock options.

00:16:09.860 --> 00:16:12.090
And stock options
have one problem,

00:16:12.090 --> 00:16:16.550
which is the only work over
a specific period of time,

00:16:16.550 --> 00:16:20.570
after which, if the
prices isn't struck,

00:16:20.570 --> 00:16:22.670
they end up being worthless.

00:16:22.670 --> 00:16:24.240
So the one thing
public companies

00:16:24.240 --> 00:16:26.230
start to spend an awful
lot of time caring

00:16:26.230 --> 00:16:28.800
about, way too much, is time.

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:30.190
They need it now.

00:16:30.190 --> 00:16:33.310
And in fact, Wall
Street loves companies

00:16:33.310 --> 00:16:35.680
that are willing to present
things early on because it

00:16:35.680 --> 00:16:39.595
means that they can predict more
clearly what the world's going

00:16:39.595 --> 00:16:43.790
to look like than what natural
outcomes ought to allow.

00:16:43.790 --> 00:16:48.870
So they can say, General Mills
is going to earn $1.50 this

00:16:48.870 --> 00:16:52.970
quarter, and General Mills
will earn $1.50 this quarter.

00:16:52.970 --> 00:16:55.154
They won't really earn
it, but they'll report it.

00:16:55.154 --> 00:16:57.070
And they'll do that again
and again and again.

00:16:57.070 --> 00:16:59.810
And then over time,
by taking steps

00:16:59.810 --> 00:17:02.160
that get the outcome,
to meet the target,

00:17:02.160 --> 00:17:05.069
to keep the share price up--
because there's no volatility,

00:17:05.069 --> 00:17:09.197
it's all predictable-- they
hollow out the franchise.

00:17:09.197 --> 00:17:11.030
Just the opposite of
what we're looking for.

00:17:11.030 --> 00:17:12.405
We're looking for
businesses that

00:17:12.405 --> 00:17:16.589
are willing to completely
thrash the near term in pursuit

00:17:16.589 --> 00:17:17.849
of the long term.

00:17:17.849 --> 00:17:19.300
But in order to
do that, they have

00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:22.490
to have security in one
issue, which is control.

00:17:22.490 --> 00:17:24.339
That's where the
family-controlled company

00:17:24.339 --> 00:17:29.450
comes into play, because they
can, with their super vote,

00:17:29.450 --> 00:17:34.920
defend against the pressures
that normal managements are

00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:38.400
willing to assume in
the complicit bargain

00:17:38.400 --> 00:17:41.350
that they have with stock
option-driven compensation.

00:17:41.350 --> 00:17:42.780
I'll fast forward for a second.

00:17:42.780 --> 00:17:46.140
I pulled this from the
Google founding principles.

00:17:46.140 --> 00:17:49.420
And right at the heart of
what Google talks about,

00:17:49.420 --> 00:17:51.750
and what I think gives
you such endurance,

00:17:51.750 --> 00:17:57.120
is this structure, this
third paragraph down,

00:17:57.120 --> 00:17:58.910
second sentence. "This
structure will also

00:17:58.910 --> 00:18:00.860
make it easier for
our management team

00:18:00.860 --> 00:18:03.910
to follow the long-term
innovative approach emphasized

00:18:03.910 --> 00:18:05.810
earlier."

00:18:05.810 --> 00:18:08.950
They have the
management's back covered,

00:18:08.950 --> 00:18:12.360
and they allow, from that
standpoint-- investments have

00:18:12.360 --> 00:18:15.750
a very long payback,
but upfront burden

00:18:15.750 --> 00:18:18.960
to take place at full
amounts, because it's

00:18:18.960 --> 00:18:22.290
my belief that most public
companies, the error

00:18:22.290 --> 00:18:25.530
is on under-investment
upfront to make sure

00:18:25.530 --> 00:18:31.590
that the results are,
in effect, overstated.

00:18:31.590 --> 00:18:33.610
Now I use the term
capacity to suffer.

00:18:33.610 --> 00:18:34.670
It's a funny one.

00:18:34.670 --> 00:18:37.710
It was partly derived
from another investor

00:18:37.710 --> 00:18:39.490
you may have met with
or heard of called

00:18:39.490 --> 00:18:42.910
Jean-Marie Eveillard, who runs
SoGen's International Fund.

00:18:42.910 --> 00:18:44.890
He was quite an early
international investor.

00:18:44.890 --> 00:18:46.600
And at a Columbia
function I was at,

00:18:46.600 --> 00:18:48.920
the business school,
somebody asked him

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:51.790
what he looked for in
analysts when he was hiring

00:18:51.790 --> 00:18:53.730
to build as investment team.

00:18:53.730 --> 00:18:57.710
And without a moment, he
said, the capacity to suffer.

00:18:57.710 --> 00:19:00.500
And I thought that was an
appropriate definition.

00:19:00.500 --> 00:19:04.930
And the reason he said that
is that it's so rare to find

00:19:04.930 --> 00:19:07.240
that in America,
because as a country,

00:19:07.240 --> 00:19:10.230
we always think that every
single day should be better

00:19:10.230 --> 00:19:12.490
than the prior day.

00:19:12.490 --> 00:19:14.360
Actually, there's a
great quote in the book

00:19:14.360 --> 00:19:17.250
that I just read, "Work Rules."

00:19:17.250 --> 00:19:21.010
And he talks about a guy who
was in a cubicle, and he said,

00:19:21.010 --> 00:19:25.190
every day of his life is
worse than the day before.

00:19:25.190 --> 00:19:26.440
That's the capacity to suffer.

00:19:26.440 --> 00:19:32.940
But in the investment world,
the capacity to suffer

00:19:32.940 --> 00:19:35.030
is hard to find.

00:19:35.030 --> 00:19:39.610
People expect returns to
come easily, regularly,

00:19:39.610 --> 00:19:40.450
and they don't.

00:19:40.450 --> 00:19:43.190
And so his recognition
was that you

00:19:43.190 --> 00:19:45.840
have to have people
in the investment

00:19:45.840 --> 00:19:49.260
business
constitutionally prepared

00:19:49.260 --> 00:19:52.690
to have deferred results.

00:19:52.690 --> 00:19:53.190
All right.

00:19:53.190 --> 00:19:55.300
So if we start out
believing that we're

00:19:55.300 --> 00:19:58.190
going to hold something
for a very long time, what

00:19:58.190 --> 00:20:01.350
it needs to have is the
capacity to reinvest internally.

00:20:01.350 --> 00:20:05.410
For me, I used consumer
brands as the industry

00:20:05.410 --> 00:20:09.330
through which I invest because
they tend to be very enduring.

00:20:09.330 --> 00:20:11.570
You think about Communist China.

00:20:11.570 --> 00:20:15.860
After the veil lifted and
commerce could go back in,

00:20:15.860 --> 00:20:19.960
the number one cigarette in
Communist China the next day

00:20:19.960 --> 00:20:22.300
was a cigarette that
hadn't been in the country

00:20:22.300 --> 00:20:24.040
for 55 years of Communism.

00:20:24.040 --> 00:20:26.440
It was the old British
American tobacco

00:20:26.440 --> 00:20:29.300
brand called State Express 555.

00:20:29.300 --> 00:20:32.310
Hadn't been in the market,
but somehow it was still

00:20:32.310 --> 00:20:34.770
in the brains of the consumer.

00:20:34.770 --> 00:20:38.270
Same thing with Romania when
the wall went down in Romania.

00:20:38.270 --> 00:20:40.570
The number one thing
that the Romanians wanted

00:20:40.570 --> 00:20:42.260
was Chesterfield cigarettes.

00:20:42.260 --> 00:20:44.250
Well, you can't even
find them anymore.

00:20:44.250 --> 00:20:49.750
But that brand endured for 55
years in the consumer psyche.

00:20:49.750 --> 00:20:53.160
And what we look
for is the ability

00:20:53.160 --> 00:20:55.810
to reinvest behind those brands.

00:20:55.810 --> 00:20:59.490
The strength of the
brands tend to allow

00:20:59.490 --> 00:21:02.540
for more regular free cash flow
because of the pricing power

00:21:02.540 --> 00:21:03.730
that you get.

00:21:03.730 --> 00:21:07.070
The likelihood of finding
owner-minded businesses

00:21:07.070 --> 00:21:10.730
goes up with consumer
brands because they

00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:13.380
tend to have been, over the
life of the company, more

00:21:13.380 --> 00:21:15.020
self-funding.

00:21:15.020 --> 00:21:18.100
You think about why it is that
most American companies don't

00:21:18.100 --> 00:21:20.170
end up with control
shareholders,

00:21:20.170 --> 00:21:22.940
because if you're in
a crummy business,

00:21:22.940 --> 00:21:25.340
it takes a lot of money to grow.

00:21:25.340 --> 00:21:28.170
And you have to raise
additional equity again

00:21:28.170 --> 00:21:29.955
and again and again
to fund the growth.

00:21:29.955 --> 00:21:32.630
And at the end, if it's a
sufficiently competitive crummy

00:21:32.630 --> 00:21:37.840
business, you're going to have
horrible results and no control

00:21:37.840 --> 00:21:38.890
shareholder.

00:21:38.890 --> 00:21:41.250
The presence of a
business that still

00:21:41.250 --> 00:21:45.590
has control held by the family
is an evidence of the fact

00:21:45.590 --> 00:21:48.640
that the business is, at its
heart, quite cash generative.

00:21:48.640 --> 00:21:51.850
Now it's not enough just
to be cash generative.

00:21:51.850 --> 00:21:54.960
What you really want
is to have the capacity

00:21:54.960 --> 00:21:57.910
to have that cash that the
mature markets deliver,

00:21:57.910 --> 00:22:00.890
in the world of consumer brands,
available for reinvestment

00:22:00.890 --> 00:22:05.660
globally where 95% of the
world exists in population,

00:22:05.660 --> 00:22:08.620
and where GDPs are
escalating, and where

00:22:08.620 --> 00:22:11.020
consumer disposable
income is just growing.

00:22:11.020 --> 00:22:16.500
And so we want to have brands
that have relevance abroad,

00:22:16.500 --> 00:22:19.300
which gives them the capacity
to reinvest mature market cash

00:22:19.300 --> 00:22:21.670
flows into growing markets.

00:22:21.670 --> 00:22:24.630
It leads this portfolio
that I oversee

00:22:24.630 --> 00:22:27.880
to be primarily European.

00:22:27.880 --> 00:22:29.050
That's for a couple reasons.

00:22:29.050 --> 00:22:34.100
One, the European managements
aren't nearly so accustomed

00:22:34.100 --> 00:22:37.360
to compensation based
on equity options.

00:22:37.360 --> 00:22:39.690
And so this notion of
having to do something

00:22:39.690 --> 00:22:42.950
quickly-- and fabricate
numbers to make sure

00:22:42.950 --> 00:22:45.574
that the Wall Street
analysts are pleased enough

00:22:45.574 --> 00:22:47.740
to keep the stock price
high enough for your options

00:22:47.740 --> 00:22:49.950
to be worth something--
doesn't exist over there.

00:22:49.950 --> 00:22:53.550
They pay people cash.

00:22:53.550 --> 00:22:59.700
The brands that exists in
Europe have been abroad more

00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:03.700
historically, and hence are
more embedded in the culture.

00:23:03.700 --> 00:23:07.460
In India you have
Hindustan Lever.

00:23:07.460 --> 00:23:09.170
Well, that's Unilever.

00:23:09.170 --> 00:23:11.580
You have Cadbury of India.

00:23:11.580 --> 00:23:12.770
That's Cadbury Schweppes.

00:23:12.770 --> 00:23:14.690
You have Nestle of India.

00:23:14.690 --> 00:23:17.110
They've been around, in
the case of those three,

00:23:17.110 --> 00:23:18.840
for at least 50 years.

00:23:18.840 --> 00:23:24.860
And their aspirational
character was developed

00:23:24.860 --> 00:23:27.740
over that period of time.

00:23:27.740 --> 00:23:32.300
And that aspirational
character gives pricing power.

00:23:32.300 --> 00:23:36.597
And that pricing power
allows for reinvestment.

00:23:36.597 --> 00:23:38.055
So we're looking
for global brands.

00:23:38.055 --> 00:23:40.660
We like the developing
emerging markets,

00:23:40.660 --> 00:23:44.610
because that's where the newly
formed demand is arising.

00:23:44.610 --> 00:23:48.440
That's where the markets
are un-invested in.

00:23:48.440 --> 00:23:50.910
And that's where
GDPs are rising.

00:23:50.910 --> 00:23:53.780
Everything I'm
telling you, actually,

00:23:53.780 --> 00:23:57.730
was more true as a context
two years ago than today.

00:23:57.730 --> 00:24:03.850
If you think about the stories
of the current world, collapse

00:24:03.850 --> 00:24:07.050
of commodity prices, pulling
back of manufacturing,

00:24:07.050 --> 00:24:08.280
China coming back.

00:24:08.280 --> 00:24:13.290
So lots of what I've built
into my investment thesis

00:24:13.290 --> 00:24:15.810
is sort of in flux.

00:24:15.810 --> 00:24:19.690
And it's an interesting time.

00:24:19.690 --> 00:24:21.930
But it certainly has
been, for the past 25

00:24:21.930 --> 00:24:23.530
years of the course
of my investment

00:24:23.530 --> 00:24:27.300
creator, a one-way tailwind,
the opening up of markets

00:24:27.300 --> 00:24:30.450
leading to the transparency and
liberalization of societies,

00:24:30.450 --> 00:24:33.280
leaving people free to buy
things that they'd long aspired

00:24:33.280 --> 00:24:36.090
to, leading our
companies to have a place

00:24:36.090 --> 00:24:38.990
to pour back their free
cash flow into meeting

00:24:38.990 --> 00:24:42.340
that consumer need as a group.

00:24:42.340 --> 00:24:43.350
What else do you need?

00:24:43.350 --> 00:24:47.330
And this also favors
international community.

00:24:47.330 --> 00:24:49.529
One thing you need to
expand internationally--

00:24:49.529 --> 00:24:51.820
if that's where your growth
is going to come from-- you

00:24:51.820 --> 00:24:57.070
better have multilingual
and multicultural managers.

00:24:57.070 --> 00:24:58.990
Multilingual surfaces
quite quickly.

00:24:58.990 --> 00:25:00.450
In this audience,
how many people

00:25:00.450 --> 00:25:01.991
here speak more than
three languages?

00:25:05.750 --> 00:25:08.580
Good It's rare.

00:25:08.580 --> 00:25:11.470
It's really rare
in North America.

00:25:11.470 --> 00:25:13.640
It's not at all rare in Europe.

00:25:13.640 --> 00:25:16.450
So at Nestle, I think the top
100 people in the management

00:25:16.450 --> 00:25:18.300
team speak four languages.

00:25:18.300 --> 00:25:24.190
And at Kraft Foods in
Illinois they speak 0.9.

00:25:24.190 --> 00:25:26.170
Multicultural.

00:25:26.170 --> 00:25:27.920
That's important.

00:25:27.920 --> 00:25:29.580
Let me ask somebody
a question here.

00:25:29.580 --> 00:25:31.560
How many people-- just
by raising your hand--

00:25:31.560 --> 00:25:34.860
how many people have a
favorite cricket player?

00:25:37.650 --> 00:25:39.480
See, you're a very
unusual company.

00:25:39.480 --> 00:25:42.390
That's what makes Google great.

00:25:42.390 --> 00:25:44.430
Nowhere else, if I
ask that question,

00:25:44.430 --> 00:25:47.400
will a single hand go up.

00:25:47.400 --> 00:25:50.750
1.7 billion people go
to sleep each night

00:25:50.750 --> 00:25:53.059
thinking about their
favorite cricket player.

00:25:53.059 --> 00:25:55.225
And if you're going to be
effective internationally,

00:25:55.225 --> 00:25:56.808
you probably want
to have somebody who

00:25:56.808 --> 00:25:59.840
understands that story line.

00:25:59.840 --> 00:26:04.430
So the capacity to reinvest
is not democratically shared.

00:26:04.430 --> 00:26:06.280
I made light of Kraft.

00:26:06.280 --> 00:26:08.600
Indeed, we had and
sold all of our stake

00:26:08.600 --> 00:26:12.060
in Kraft because of their
provincial portfolio

00:26:12.060 --> 00:26:13.780
and their lack of
natural reinvestment.

00:26:13.780 --> 00:26:16.740
They tried to go into China,
they failed, they came out.

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:18.650
They had no people to
develop the market.

00:26:18.650 --> 00:26:20.560
They didn't understand it.

00:26:20.560 --> 00:26:23.110
And it's a domestic
company, and it's

00:26:23.110 --> 00:26:26.350
a company that's made lots
of money selling cheese

00:26:26.350 --> 00:26:30.030
and cookies and
meat to Americans.

00:26:30.030 --> 00:26:31.490
And America was a
big enough market

00:26:31.490 --> 00:26:35.410
that it kept their
ambitions fully staffed.

00:26:35.410 --> 00:26:37.870
But they had no capacity
to go internationally.

00:26:37.870 --> 00:26:40.920
We want businesses that can.

00:26:40.920 --> 00:26:42.090
Nestle, Unilever.

00:26:42.090 --> 00:26:44.564
They have the bench strength,
they have the brands,

00:26:44.564 --> 00:26:46.730
they have the cash flow,
they have the understanding

00:26:46.730 --> 00:26:48.360
of where the puck's going.

00:26:48.360 --> 00:26:50.000
Now in order to do
it the right way,

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.560
you have to have the
capacity to suffer.

00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:55.750
That means that when you
open up a new market,

00:26:55.750 --> 00:27:00.010
you're going to have unabsorbed
fixed costs in spades,

00:27:00.010 --> 00:27:02.760
and that will burden
current income.

00:27:02.760 --> 00:27:07.070
If you're not protected
through major shareholders who

00:27:07.070 --> 00:27:10.290
support that long-term vision,
I can assure you-- today

00:27:10.290 --> 00:27:13.280
especially so-- you
will have any number

00:27:13.280 --> 00:27:17.460
of a dozen different
activists come in by 1% or 2%

00:27:17.460 --> 00:27:19.770
of your company
and demand better.

00:27:19.770 --> 00:27:20.640
You can do better.

00:27:20.640 --> 00:27:21.820
If not, we'll kick you out.

00:27:21.820 --> 00:27:25.410
And no management team wants
to do that, especially midway

00:27:25.410 --> 00:27:27.870
through an investment cycle.

00:27:27.870 --> 00:27:29.640
I'll give you a quick example.

00:27:29.640 --> 00:27:31.470
We own shares of
Cadbury Schweppes.

00:27:31.470 --> 00:27:32.940
It's a terrific business.

00:27:32.940 --> 00:27:34.150
They had three pillars.

00:27:34.150 --> 00:27:37.026
They had gum, chocolate,
and hard candy.

00:27:37.026 --> 00:27:39.150
Each one of those came from
a different background.

00:27:39.150 --> 00:27:42.090
in Each one was dominant
different parts of the world.

00:27:42.090 --> 00:27:43.580
Put it all together.

00:27:43.580 --> 00:27:47.605
They had great market presence
in parts of the world that

00:27:47.605 --> 00:27:49.770
had been massively underserved.

00:27:49.770 --> 00:27:53.110
The joy of eating sweet things.

00:27:53.110 --> 00:27:54.130
So what do they do?

00:27:54.130 --> 00:27:57.140
They decide that they try to
launch the business in China.

00:27:57.140 --> 00:28:00.860
And they start out in Hong
Kong, Beijing, and Shanghai.

00:28:00.860 --> 00:28:03.310
And they knock the ball
out of the court, everyone

00:28:03.310 --> 00:28:04.560
believes it's a good business.

00:28:04.560 --> 00:28:05.680
The Chinese line up.

00:28:05.680 --> 00:28:07.080
They like it.

00:28:07.080 --> 00:28:11.460
They go to 200 of the
next cities in line.

00:28:11.460 --> 00:28:13.990
So that takes you down to
cities of a million or more,

00:28:13.990 --> 00:28:15.710
but there are 200 of them.

00:28:15.710 --> 00:28:17.600
Now the suffering really starts.

00:28:17.600 --> 00:28:19.610
Now they're spending
a lot of money.

00:28:19.610 --> 00:28:21.040
They have to
introduce the brand,

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:22.956
they have to build
awareness and all the rest.

00:28:22.956 --> 00:28:24.890
And they do it
across 200 cities.

00:28:24.890 --> 00:28:28.580
Now I heard from the CEO of
the company sort of midstream

00:28:28.580 --> 00:28:29.540
through this.

00:28:29.540 --> 00:28:32.000
He understood that the
investment spending

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:35.480
was going to just overwhelm the
reported profits out of Hong

00:28:35.480 --> 00:28:38.450
Kong, Shanghai, and Beijing.

00:28:38.450 --> 00:28:41.510
In fact, they'd show losses
for as long as they could see.

00:28:41.510 --> 00:28:45.230
And every year that went by
and they invested like this,

00:28:45.230 --> 00:28:50.240
they built net worth because
they converted consumers

00:28:50.240 --> 00:28:53.280
who became loyalists and who
had lifetime consumer patterns.

00:28:53.280 --> 00:28:57.360
And you can know the upfront
value of a converted customer

00:28:57.360 --> 00:29:00.260
addicted to sweet things.

00:29:00.260 --> 00:29:03.550
They were midway through the
process, losing a lot of money.

00:29:03.550 --> 00:29:06.310
Along comes Nelson Peltz,
knocks on the door and says,

00:29:06.310 --> 00:29:07.930
you gotta do better.

00:29:07.930 --> 00:29:10.250
The numbers just
aren't advancing.

00:29:10.250 --> 00:29:11.570
You have to do something.

00:29:11.570 --> 00:29:12.970
Give us some earnings.

00:29:12.970 --> 00:29:16.080
So the board and the CEO
went home over the weekend,

00:29:16.080 --> 00:29:17.940
came back and said, right.

00:29:17.940 --> 00:29:20.180
We think we have China wrong.

00:29:20.180 --> 00:29:22.702
That investment work we're
doing in those 200 cities.

00:29:22.702 --> 00:29:24.160
We're way out in
front of our skis.

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:25.500
It's just not working.

00:29:25.500 --> 00:29:26.600
Let's close it.

00:29:26.600 --> 00:29:29.180
Now with that, they
manufactured income

00:29:29.180 --> 00:29:31.800
because they stopped
bearing the costs

00:29:31.800 --> 00:29:33.380
of investing for the future.

00:29:33.380 --> 00:29:36.070
They destroyed wealth,
because all the people

00:29:36.070 --> 00:29:39.660
who had bought on board the
brands now no longer could

00:29:39.660 --> 00:29:40.710
source them.

00:29:40.710 --> 00:29:43.040
And away went the
equity, the goodwill

00:29:43.040 --> 00:29:45.720
that they had created through
that investment spending

00:29:45.720 --> 00:29:47.010
midstream.

00:29:47.010 --> 00:29:49.110
And they lacked the
capacity to suffer,

00:29:49.110 --> 00:29:52.310
because when a raider came
and rattled their cage,

00:29:52.310 --> 00:29:53.550
they said fine.

00:29:53.550 --> 00:29:55.580
We'll do just what you need.

00:29:55.580 --> 00:29:57.540
We have a handful
of examples here,

00:29:57.540 --> 00:29:59.510
which I'll go through
quite quickly.

00:29:59.510 --> 00:30:02.090
I'd say the best
example of a company,

00:30:02.090 --> 00:30:04.530
too, that had the
capacity to suffer.

00:30:04.530 --> 00:30:07.067
One is inside this room.

00:30:07.067 --> 00:30:09.150
You know, you think about
all the kind of projects

00:30:09.150 --> 00:30:14.770
that Google incubates,
burdening profit

00:30:14.770 --> 00:30:18.170
with an idea, maybe, of where
it'll end up, but in some cases

00:30:18.170 --> 00:30:19.600
not even.

00:30:19.600 --> 00:30:22.710
That's extraordinarily powerful.

00:30:22.710 --> 00:30:26.212
And you have lots to
show as a result of that.

00:30:26.212 --> 00:30:28.409
That scale would be a
very interesting one,

00:30:28.409 --> 00:30:29.950
because I think you
have an awful lot

00:30:29.950 --> 00:30:32.700
to show for the
willingness to suffer.

00:30:32.700 --> 00:30:33.650
And Amazon.

00:30:33.650 --> 00:30:36.570
Amazon's way out,
even beyond you guys.

00:30:36.570 --> 00:30:38.620
I'm not sure that they'll
ever report a profit.

00:30:38.620 --> 00:30:42.279
But they certainly have
the capacity to suffer.

00:30:42.279 --> 00:30:43.320
So do their shareholders.

00:30:43.320 --> 00:30:46.150
Well, of course they
get rewarded for it.

00:30:46.150 --> 00:30:47.490
The price has gone up so much.

00:30:50.050 --> 00:30:55.780
So the businesses that we'll
look at are more traditional.

00:30:55.780 --> 00:30:57.304
Berkshire is the best one.

00:30:57.304 --> 00:30:58.720
That's why I learned
this subject.

00:30:58.720 --> 00:31:00.520
Warren talks about
it all the time.

00:31:00.520 --> 00:31:02.470
But Geico's a great example.

00:31:02.470 --> 00:31:04.820
Much like
confectionery in China,

00:31:04.820 --> 00:31:10.930
it's expensive, it turns out,
to bring on an auto insured.

00:31:10.930 --> 00:31:15.360
And so when Warren
bought controlled Geico,

00:31:15.360 --> 00:31:19.470
he asked the CEO why they only
had two million policyholders,

00:31:19.470 --> 00:31:22.630
and the CEO said, because
it's too expensive to grow.

00:31:22.630 --> 00:31:24.840
Every new policy
we put on the book

00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:28.890
loses $250 in the first year.

00:31:28.890 --> 00:31:36.410
And ongoing insured make $150
per year of operating profit

00:31:36.410 --> 00:31:37.490
for the company.

00:31:37.490 --> 00:31:42.160
So you have two million
policyholders making $150 year,

00:31:42.160 --> 00:31:46.070
so they were reporting
$300 million of profits.

00:31:46.070 --> 00:31:51.110
And if they wanted to grow
a million new policies

00:31:51.110 --> 00:31:53.980
the next year--
because as Warren said,

00:31:53.980 --> 00:31:56.350
they had the best
business, under-penetrated,

00:31:56.350 --> 00:31:58.970
the market should
have more of them.

00:31:58.970 --> 00:32:02.160
So why not grow it by a
million policyholders?

00:32:02.160 --> 00:32:04.520
What would happen to the
operating income that year?

00:32:04.520 --> 00:32:07.700
It would go from
300 to 50 assuming

00:32:07.700 --> 00:32:09.720
that the other business
didn't grow at all.

00:32:09.720 --> 00:32:14.370
Now no public company can
endure that kind of volatility.

00:32:14.370 --> 00:32:18.480
The activists would be
on that thing so quickly.

00:32:18.480 --> 00:32:21.190
Inside Berkshire,
it didn't matter.

00:32:21.190 --> 00:32:24.030
Warren controls
40%+ of the stock.

00:32:24.030 --> 00:32:25.760
He's never told
investors that he's

00:32:25.760 --> 00:32:28.260
in the business of
manufacturing reported earnings.

00:32:28.260 --> 00:32:29.650
No one get stock options.

00:32:29.650 --> 00:32:32.050
He gets paid $100,000 a year.

00:32:32.050 --> 00:32:36.040
It's all about owner's
equity, intrinsic value,

00:32:36.040 --> 00:32:39.400
and how do you grow that with
certainty as best you can?

00:32:39.400 --> 00:32:45.180
Well, no better reinvestment
than to take that $2 million

00:32:45.180 --> 00:32:52.210
insured base up because of its
persistency and its low claims,

00:32:52.210 --> 00:32:55.250
lack of adverse
selection as they grew.

00:32:55.250 --> 00:32:58.280
They had a lot of room.

00:32:58.280 --> 00:33:02.860
And by the way, even though the
first year cost, reported loss

00:33:02.860 --> 00:33:05.760
of a new insured
was $250 upfront,

00:33:05.760 --> 00:33:09.040
the moment they signed up the
net present value, lifetime

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:12.630
value of each insured, $2,000.

00:33:12.630 --> 00:33:17.950
That's $150 stretched out
forever, brought back.

00:33:17.950 --> 00:33:23.030
Now, so for the
mere inconvenience

00:33:23.030 --> 00:33:25.710
of reporting a
$250 loss upfront,

00:33:25.710 --> 00:33:28.550
they put on $2,000 of value.

00:33:28.550 --> 00:33:29.870
Warren got it.

00:33:29.870 --> 00:33:33.950
Today, 14 years later, they
have 11 million policyholders.

00:33:33.950 --> 00:33:36.590
And in the annual report
he said to investors,

00:33:36.590 --> 00:33:39.670
because he's a fair
partner, if you're

00:33:39.670 --> 00:33:42.050
thinking about selling
the business, your shares

00:33:42.050 --> 00:33:45.860
in Berkshire, understand that
book value doesn't capture all

00:33:45.860 --> 00:33:47.950
that we've got that's good.

00:33:47.950 --> 00:33:51.750
And he said, for instance, at
Geico we've added $20 billion

00:33:51.750 --> 00:33:53.360
of value since we bought it.

00:33:53.360 --> 00:33:55.580
Now that's that $20
billion that comes

00:33:55.580 --> 00:33:59.440
from those 9,000 new insured.

00:33:59.440 --> 00:34:01.050
And the only way
you get there is

00:34:01.050 --> 00:34:04.040
by having the capacity to
let the income statement

00:34:04.040 --> 00:34:05.190
bear the burden.

00:34:05.190 --> 00:34:08.520
And over that time, they
took their annual ad spending

00:34:08.520 --> 00:34:11.409
from $30 million
up to $1 billion.

00:34:11.409 --> 00:34:14.570
And you'd all know that,
because watching television

00:34:14.570 --> 00:34:19.679
is really a series of Geico
advertisements these days.

00:34:19.679 --> 00:34:23.320
Another thing that
Berkshire did was,

00:34:23.320 --> 00:34:24.659
the equity index put options.

00:34:24.659 --> 00:34:28.040
There's a group
that had $37 billion

00:34:28.040 --> 00:34:31.110
worth of equities,
market value equities,

00:34:31.110 --> 00:34:33.350
around the world for
different markets.

00:34:33.350 --> 00:34:36.480
And whatever the
reason, that group

00:34:36.480 --> 00:34:40.440
had to be able to say
to their counterparties

00:34:40.440 --> 00:34:43.550
that that $37 billion
was not at risk.

00:34:43.550 --> 00:34:45.469
They needed for
their collateral,

00:34:45.469 --> 00:34:48.100
whatever the reasons,
to have $37 billion.

00:34:48.100 --> 00:34:51.070
And so Warren was
asked to insure

00:34:51.070 --> 00:34:55.070
against the potential for that
portfolio to decline in value.

00:34:55.070 --> 00:34:57.640
He sold them a put option.

00:34:57.640 --> 00:35:02.620
In return, we received
$5.3 billion to invest,

00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:05.060
unfettered, for 18 years.

00:35:05.060 --> 00:35:07.510
It was non-callable and
it had no collateral

00:35:07.510 --> 00:35:11.450
posting requirements, which are
the killers in this business.

00:35:11.450 --> 00:35:16.990
So why did Warren get
$5 billion to insure

00:35:16.990 --> 00:35:20.830
against the decline of
equities over 18 years

00:35:20.830 --> 00:35:25.670
when, likely, the course of
equity values is up over time?

00:35:25.670 --> 00:35:29.530
It's because the people
who needed that insurance

00:35:29.530 --> 00:35:31.950
had nowhere else to go.

00:35:31.950 --> 00:35:33.320
First, Warren had the capital.

00:35:33.320 --> 00:35:36.890
He had $50 billion of spare
cash which sort of buttressed

00:35:36.890 --> 00:35:39.040
his claims-paying appeal.

00:35:39.040 --> 00:35:40.790
Other people who might
take the $5 billion

00:35:40.790 --> 00:35:43.720
don't have the capital
balance sheet or the culture

00:35:43.720 --> 00:35:45.980
to provide for the
ultimate payment

00:35:45.980 --> 00:35:48.980
if the world went to zero
and they owed $37 billion.

00:35:48.980 --> 00:35:52.550
Warren has that, and the
culture would honor that.

00:35:52.550 --> 00:35:54.300
The other thing, the
more important thing,

00:35:54.300 --> 00:35:56.420
was nobody else would
touch this stuff,

00:35:56.420 --> 00:36:01.760
because every quarter there is
a mark to market requirement.

00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:05.620
And it absolutely
crushes reported profits.

00:36:05.620 --> 00:36:06.470
So for example.

00:36:06.470 --> 00:36:08.590
After they signed it,
received the $5 billion,

00:36:08.590 --> 00:36:11.150
the equity world
markets collapsed

00:36:11.150 --> 00:36:15.520
and they had six quarters
in a row of over $1 billion

00:36:15.520 --> 00:36:18.980
worth of charges to
the income statement,

00:36:18.980 --> 00:36:21.020
some periods as
much as $3 billion,

00:36:21.020 --> 00:36:23.412
because global
equities collapsed.

00:36:23.412 --> 00:36:24.870
And every time it
collapsed, they'd

00:36:24.870 --> 00:36:27.370
have to pass through
the reported profits,

00:36:27.370 --> 00:36:28.940
the mark to market.

00:36:28.940 --> 00:36:29.730
OK.

00:36:29.730 --> 00:36:31.760
So at the end of the
day he had $13 billion

00:36:31.760 --> 00:36:37.540
less in earnings
cumulatively over that time.

00:36:37.540 --> 00:36:39.840
But he had $5 billion
which he had put to work.

00:36:39.840 --> 00:36:45.660
And that's sort of the
last story about Berkshire.

00:36:45.660 --> 00:36:48.600
Another way in which you could
see his capacity to suffer

00:36:48.600 --> 00:36:54.120
added enormous value was that
during the crisis-- well,

00:36:54.120 --> 00:36:57.640
during the period leading up
to the financial crisis of 2007

00:36:57.640 --> 00:36:59.620
and 2008, Warren, at
the annual meetings,

00:36:59.620 --> 00:37:02.500
always lamented the fact that
he had $50 billion cash hanging

00:37:02.500 --> 00:37:08.390
around on which he
was only earning .01%.

00:37:10.930 --> 00:37:12.520
And that's the safe return.

00:37:12.520 --> 00:37:16.000
That's sort of the federal
treasury bills that are secure.

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:18.417
Since he kept it in cash, he
might as well keep it secure.

00:37:18.417 --> 00:37:19.583
But he was only making .01%.

00:37:19.583 --> 00:37:20.150
01%.

00:37:20.150 --> 00:37:24.300
If he had standard
company practices,

00:37:24.300 --> 00:37:26.720
he never would have
kept $50 billion of cash

00:37:26.720 --> 00:37:27.560
in overnight money.

00:37:27.560 --> 00:37:30.110
He would have gone
out three, 10, 14, 40

00:37:30.110 --> 00:37:34.360
years on a bond portfolio and
would have had a 4% yield.

00:37:34.360 --> 00:37:37.720
He kept it at .01% because
he didn't trust inflation

00:37:37.720 --> 00:37:42.160
or credits to support
having $50 billion

00:37:42.160 --> 00:37:45.430
in longer duration investments.

00:37:45.430 --> 00:37:49.530
The difference between 4%
and 0.1% on $50 billion

00:37:49.530 --> 00:37:52.160
is $2 billion a year.

00:37:52.160 --> 00:37:56.230
That's the amount he
suffered by under reporting,

00:37:56.230 --> 00:38:00.330
because he kept his money
in liquid treasuries.

00:38:00.330 --> 00:38:03.480
That requires a lot of
suffering because $2 billion

00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:06.210
is a lot of money,
even to Warren.

00:38:06.210 --> 00:38:11.620
Now ironically, to show you
how American companies behave,

00:38:11.620 --> 00:38:15.800
at the same time that Warren was
belly aching about only making

00:38:15.800 --> 00:38:23.660
.1%, General Electric had taken
$100 billion of their borrowing

00:38:23.660 --> 00:38:27.530
and brought it into
commercial paper overnight

00:38:27.530 --> 00:38:30.780
to capture those same low rates.

00:38:30.780 --> 00:38:33.620
Now it's a different story
for General Electric, though.

00:38:33.620 --> 00:38:37.200
You have businesses that have
long-term funding requirements

00:38:37.200 --> 00:38:42.440
where you can't responsibly
borrow overnight to meet.

00:38:42.440 --> 00:38:46.350
You can do so if your goal
is to manufacture earnings.

00:38:46.350 --> 00:38:49.400
And off $100 billion in
the overnight market,

00:38:49.400 --> 00:38:53.290
where they might be earning
2%-- they may be paying to 2/10

00:38:53.290 --> 00:38:57.230
of 1%, let's say, maybe even
.03% in the commercial paper

00:38:57.230 --> 00:39:02.540
market-- they should have been
paying 4%, exactly like Warren.

00:39:02.540 --> 00:39:06.200
In their case, they should have
stretched out their liability

00:39:06.200 --> 00:39:08.460
structure.

00:39:08.460 --> 00:39:10.940
But by taking it all
into commercial paper,

00:39:10.940 --> 00:39:14.840
investment bankers assured them
that they could swap them out

00:39:14.840 --> 00:39:15.430
at any minute.

00:39:15.430 --> 00:39:16.610
They could go back long.

00:39:16.610 --> 00:39:19.170
They could go into yen,
any currency they wanted.

00:39:19.170 --> 00:39:22.360
It was just a number
after all, wasn't it?

00:39:22.360 --> 00:39:24.480
Well, they forgot
one thing, which

00:39:24.480 --> 00:39:28.030
is that overnight
markets can shut down.

00:39:28.030 --> 00:39:34.190
And when Lehman burst, GE had
$100 billion of overnight money

00:39:34.190 --> 00:39:35.960
that they couldn't roll.

00:39:35.960 --> 00:39:38.240
Warren, happily, had
$50 billion which

00:39:38.240 --> 00:39:40.190
he could use to help them out.

00:39:40.190 --> 00:39:44.380
And he gave them the right
to $12 billion of his money

00:39:44.380 --> 00:39:50.830
at 12% with hundreds of millions
of shares of call options.

