ran the business made
sense CEO to CEO, and down

01:06:09.310 --> 01:06:12.650
to the very bottom
of R and D, both

01:06:12.650 --> 01:06:15.390
the customer and the
technology company

01:06:15.390 --> 01:06:17.550
recognized that the
old ways were horrible.

01:06:17.550 --> 01:06:20.670
But they could never get above--
they could ever implement it

01:06:20.670 --> 01:06:22.500
because the top, who
had to approve stuff,

01:06:22.500 --> 01:06:24.750
was quite comfortable with
the way that things worked.

01:06:24.750 --> 01:06:27.083
And there would be an outside
enterprise that would then

01:06:27.083 --> 01:06:31.410
engage what they already
knew in house, because it

01:06:31.410 --> 01:06:35.280
was impossible to champion
an in-house solution

01:06:35.280 --> 01:06:39.760
against the kind of static
top that the disruptions,

01:06:39.760 --> 01:06:41.260
typically, that
happened elsewhere--

01:06:41.260 --> 01:06:46.450
but they didn't have to-- at
research level, even in those

01:06:46.450 --> 01:06:47.670
mature businesses.

01:06:47.670 --> 01:06:48.670
The awareness was there.

01:06:48.670 --> 01:06:50.920
It just couldn't get
up, and that's culture.

01:06:50.920 --> 01:06:53.200
And so ultimately, you've
got to have a culture that's

01:06:53.200 --> 01:06:59.280
willing, as it seems this one
is, to source ideas broadly

01:06:59.280 --> 01:07:02.840
and don't do so sort of
command control from the top.

01:07:02.840 --> 01:07:05.230
That at least gives you
a shot, I think, at it,

01:07:05.230 --> 01:07:10.230
because otherwise, the
technology's so fast moving,

01:07:10.230 --> 01:07:13.760
you'll quickly obsolete it
unless you've got that culture.

01:07:13.760 --> 01:07:16.290
This place may seem to
have that, in which case

01:07:16.290 --> 01:07:20.730
you've got the willingness to
destroy what you relied upon

01:07:20.730 --> 01:07:22.091
and move into other things.

01:07:22.091 --> 01:07:24.090
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
a lot in your discussion

01:07:24.090 --> 01:07:27.850
about investing in companies
that have demonstrated

01:07:27.850 --> 01:07:30.710
the capacity to invest
for the long haul,

01:07:30.710 --> 01:07:35.100
and to suffer, and to really,
like, make investments

01:07:35.100 --> 01:07:36.560
where it hurts.

01:07:36.560 --> 01:07:39.360
But the question that I come
up with, especially regarding,

01:07:39.360 --> 01:07:42.090
say, your Geico
example, is how do you

01:07:42.090 --> 01:07:44.960
distinguish companies
that are actually

01:07:44.960 --> 01:07:47.480
willing to make hard investments
that are going to pay off

01:07:47.480 --> 01:07:50.270
versus ones that are just
chasing after things that

01:07:50.270 --> 01:07:51.520
are actually to short-termism?

01:07:51.520 --> 01:07:53.811
THOMAS RUSSO: You know, it's
so interesting a question.

01:07:53.811 --> 01:07:56.900
In fact, I have a
slide that I rushed by,

01:07:56.900 --> 01:08:01.770
and it says, you know, capacity
to suffer is not enough.

01:08:01.770 --> 01:08:08.160
And I had Barnes and
Noble, and I had the Nook.

01:08:08.160 --> 01:08:09.480
And you think, what?

01:08:09.480 --> 01:08:12.070
Now Barnes and Noble's
controlled by Riggio.

01:08:12.070 --> 01:08:13.120
So he had control.

01:08:13.120 --> 01:08:15.060
So he could do it.

01:08:15.060 --> 01:08:21.505
But why would you ever want
to go after you and Apple

01:08:21.505 --> 01:08:25.500
on a laptop or a tablet
or a book reader?

01:08:25.500 --> 01:08:28.430
What possible
stupidity was that?

01:08:28.430 --> 01:08:31.080
Now mind you, along the way they
had a $1 billion for Microsoft

01:08:31.080 --> 01:08:33.240
and $600 million from Pearson.

01:08:33.240 --> 01:08:36.450
So it wasn't their money.

01:08:36.450 --> 01:08:37.960
But wow.

01:08:37.960 --> 01:08:40.060
So it's got to be right.

01:08:42.609 --> 01:08:44.800
And that's the trick.

01:08:44.800 --> 01:08:47.140
That's the only
thing that determines

01:08:47.140 --> 01:08:50.710
our returns over time
is-- for instance,

01:08:50.710 --> 01:08:57.890
I had a huge position in
newspapers going into 2000,

01:08:57.890 --> 01:09:01.069
because I often think about
a measure of whether I want

01:09:01.069 --> 01:09:05.010
to invest in business is, how
many dynastic fortunes do you

01:09:05.010 --> 01:09:06.859
realize have been made
from this business?

01:09:06.859 --> 01:09:09.510
Well, there was no
more dynastic source

01:09:09.510 --> 01:09:12.000
of fortune than the newspaper
business, historically.

01:09:12.000 --> 01:09:15.276
Every city, the most
prominent people in the city

01:09:15.276 --> 01:09:16.109
owned the newspaper.

01:09:16.109 --> 01:09:18.866
They controlled politics,
money, and everything else.

01:09:18.866 --> 01:09:20.240
And they had been
able to survive

01:09:20.240 --> 01:09:23.819
each generation of
technology by incorporating

01:09:23.819 --> 01:09:27.210
from print to radio,
radio to TV, TV

01:09:27.210 --> 01:09:29.464
to cable, cable
to something else.

01:09:29.464 --> 01:09:30.880
And then along
comes the Internet,

01:09:30.880 --> 01:09:33.149
and they say no, we
don't want to share

01:09:33.149 --> 01:09:34.899
our playground with you.

01:09:34.899 --> 01:09:38.390
And it was the most
unbelievable stupid moment

01:09:38.390 --> 01:09:41.380
in the history of
capitalism, because they

01:09:41.380 --> 01:09:44.460
had learned over the years that
to survive, they had to change.

01:09:44.460 --> 01:09:47.080
They had to do exactly what
Clayton Christensen said.

01:09:47.080 --> 01:09:49.340
They had to be
willing to kind of go

01:09:49.340 --> 01:09:51.149
into these new technologies
that threatened

01:09:51.149 --> 01:09:54.290
through exclusive
print revenue stream

01:09:54.290 --> 01:09:56.080
for radio, and then for TV.

01:09:56.080 --> 01:09:59.710
That was very Christensen-like.

01:09:59.710 --> 01:10:03.830
And along comes eBay
and Amazon, and they

01:10:03.830 --> 01:10:06.305
say no, because they were
both designed originally

01:10:06.305 --> 01:10:08.850
to incorporate a
newspaper platform.

01:10:08.850 --> 01:10:09.700
No.

01:10:09.700 --> 01:10:12.870
And that cost them dearly,
because the air went out

01:10:12.870 --> 01:10:15.590
of that balloon real fast.

01:10:15.590 --> 01:10:18.620
And so it's not enough.

01:10:18.620 --> 01:10:21.930
And it's not even necessary.

01:10:21.930 --> 01:10:23.760
I just find it to
be a place where

01:10:23.760 --> 01:10:28.510
we have had some success,
sort of thinking through what

01:10:28.510 --> 01:10:30.170
it is that we want.

01:10:30.170 --> 01:10:32.420
When we embark upon investing
in businesses that we're

01:10:32.420 --> 01:10:35.070
supposed to hold for
a really long time,

01:10:35.070 --> 01:10:36.550
I think these
ingredients help keep

01:10:36.550 --> 01:10:42.340
me focus on important
and knowable factors.

